SOCIAL CONTRACTS, to me, are necessary for societies to function as well as they have or do.<br><br>
Much has been written about the &quot;credibilty gap&quot; that came out of the sixties and seventies.  The perception of existing social contracts took a substantial beating.  I have heard solid arguements whether &quot;that&quot; was a good thing or not..<br><br>
The damage to social contracts is not new to American society or other societies for that matter.  The Bonus March of the 1930s; the treatment of Vietnam veterans during and after the war; the truth about the JFK assassination; money and politics in the nineties -- what the banks did in the 1930s -- Joe McCarthy did in the fifties to stake his claim to fame -- the seriousness of the SEATO alliance;  the list could on forever.  We all have our &quot;priorities&quot; as to what is the biggest of transgressions that affect us all.<br><br>
We can argue about the &quot;social contracts&quot; that were broken during the Vietnam Era -- the fairness of the draft -- <br>
politicians who made/ make promises based on econionic contributions -- where the moral high ground is/was during the Vietnam War.<br><br>
I personally believed in the Vietnam War, (only after going there.)  The authoritarianism of the South Vietnamese government was preferable to the North's version of communism.  Was Thieu preferable to Ho?  Remember how the boat people were treated and  accepted after the war.<br><br>
I also said &quot;give peace a chance,&quot; and &quot;marched with a sad heart as well.  I lived in a quandry when I &quot;knew&quot; the bombing was helping fellow American soldiers and wanting the war to be won or quit.<br><br>
I'd like to be able to tell the families of soldiers who died that their sons/daughters/ etc. died in a worthwhile cause, but I can't -- but I believe that they did.  That is personally hard for me to write -- I am still alive.<br><br>
I believe that the world is getting better -- it's a difficult task, however the &quot;in your face&quot; attitudes don't contribute to the larger task at hand -- which is our children.<br><br>
I once wrote that I was naive.  I'm really not.  I &quot;own&quot; a warriors jacket, and know that it will have to be worn again, not necesarily by me, but by future generations.  I'll use another of my worn out &quot;truisms&quot; -- sad, but true.<br><br>
I have made many friends on this site.  They have earned the right to call me &quot;nicknames&quot; and tease me.  I like the humor here.  I also like to call Anne &quot;pack mom.&quot;  Why shouldn't I; afterall I am her favorite -- sorry Tom.<br><br>
I wish you all a pleasant good night's sleep.  I have more thoughts, but will save them for another thread.<br><br>
Paul<br>
